--- body ---
## Context

`tests/test_robustness_observability.py::TestStepCounters::test_step1_counter_attempted`
fails with `FileNotFoundError` on `data/catalogs/unified_works.csv` in any worktree
without the DVC corpus. The code under test reads the real `CATALOGS_DIR` path
unmonkeypatched, so the test depends on the Phase-1 corpus being physically present
— which it is not in a fresh worktree or a data-less CI checkout. Found during 0247
(2026-07-11) and re-confirmed during the 0221 integration review: `make check-fast`
reports exactly this one failure (944 passed, 10 skipped, 1 failed) on a corpus-less
worktree; every other fast test passes.

This is a test-isolation defect, not a product bug: the step-1 counter logic is
fine, but the fast tier must not require the ~1.3 GB DVC corpus.

## Relevant files
- `tests/test_robustness_observability.py` — `TestStepCounters::test_step1_counter_attempted`
  (the failing test; reads real `CATALOGS_DIR`).
- `scripts/utils.py` / `pipeline_loaders` — where `CATALOGS_DIR` / `unified_works.csv`
  resolve.

## Actions
1. Either monkeypatch/fixture the corpus path so the counter reads a tiny synthetic
   `unified_works.csv` in a tmp dir, OR
2. Auto-mark the test `slow` / data-dependent (so it leaves the fast tier and only
   runs where the corpus is present).

Prefer (1) if the step-1 counter can be exercised against a minimal fixture — it
keeps observability coverage in the fast tier. Fall back to (2) if the counter
genuinely needs the full corpus.

## Test
- RED: `make check-fast` in a corpus-less worktree currently fails on this test.
- GREEN: `make check-fast` passes with no corpus present (fixture path), or the
  test is excluded from the fast tier (auto-mark).

## Invariants
- Do not weaken what the counter asserts where the corpus IS present.
- No new heavy dependency; a synthetic CSV fixture suffices.

## Exit criteria
- `make check-fast` is green in a fresh, data-less worktree.

